ce:section.ce:para:
Considering the facile synthetic procedure, stable fluorescence and high aqueous stability of the CDs, we have investigated their potential as a bioimaging probe. Herein, before using CDs for cell imaging, it is necessary to check their cytotoxicity in vitro since, in biomedical applications the cytotoxicity is an indispensable factor, and hence, the toxicity of as prepared CDs has been carried out by the conventional MTT assay in the HeLa cell lines. The cell viability of HeLa cells exhibits a small decrease after 24h, however, after 48h incubation the decrease of cell viability is somewhat higher particularly at higher concentration (Fig. 7
                        ). At higher concentrations (∼1.0mg/mL), the cells growth could be considerably inhibited by CDs. Additionally, it is also established that the cells after 24h of incubation with resultant CDs maintain their normal morphology, thus indicating good biocompatibility of the as-prepared CDs (Fig. S4). This result suggests that CDs can be used as a bioimaging probe. Furthermore, in vitro cellular uptake experiments in HeLa cells are performed. For the cellular uptake study, CD solution is incubated with HeLa cells at final concentration of 0.2mg/mL for 6h (Fig. 8
                        ). The fluorescence imaging study shows that the blue fluorescent CDs are mostly located in cell surface. This result demonstrates that the resultant biocompatible and non-toxic blue fluorescent CDs can be used as a potential bioimaging probe.
